result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Matthew A Youngbauer in court with attorney Joel Kenneth Larimore.  Amber Hahn, AAG, and Frederick Ian Bourg, DA, appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
This hearing covers 15CF156 and 15CF196; plea hearing for 15CF156 and STC for 15CF196.  Atty Larimore files Guilty Plea Questionnaire with the Court.  Hahn, have agreement; 15CF156 count 1 will enter plea; State agrees to cap to 10 yrs initial and 10 yrs e.s; read in and dismiss both counts in 15CF196; have been asked to read in and dismiss Burnett Co case15CF140; asks Ct's permission to file paperwork at a later date.  Atty Larimore agrees, Def agrees with representation of the State.  Court recites rights of defendant;  defendant understands charges and consequences; K&V waive constitutional rights.  Atty Larimore; stip to factual basis; plea to count 1 on 15CF156 of G; Courts find a factual basis and accepts plea; finds G.  15CF196 and Burnett Co 15CF140 dismissed and read in for sentencing; will allow paperwork for Burnett Co 15CF140 to be filed.  Court orders PSI.  Court orders bond will continue.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for July 5, 2016 at 02:45 pm.
Transcript of adjourned initial appearance held on December 30, 2015 before the Honorable John P. Anderson  (also preliminary hearing on 15CF156)
